content: It's a little below my knowledge because I know a lot of Microprocessors/Microcontrollers. I think it is a really good introduction for people who know nothing about the topic.

Needs to much more slowly explained for a beginner. Overuse of shortcuts that are expected by the learner to already know without much explanation of them made it difficult to follow along. Couldn't even get through the first lesson without replaying everything multiple times just to find out what the instructions were or where they were located. He explains nothing really about the design choices he uses or even what a tool is doing; he is literally just narrating himself making a minions model and doing really no actual teaching. This is a BIG mistake as someone could easily miss a step and not be able to figure out where they went wrong. A lot of reviews mentioned having difficulty following along. If multiple students need to repeatedly re-watch sections of the lesson, then the time rating is not accurate so anyone thinking about taking this should be aware it is not only going to be ~2 hours unless you are more of an intermediate user. There are better blender tutorials out there, don't waste your time struggling through this. He does manage to actually do what he says (create a character from scratch) so this gets some points for that but don't expect to actually learn how to this from this course in a way that allows you to do so on your own, without help, using a different character.
He is very talented at his work. I am just not as experienced at doing this as I hoped. I take nothing away from his teaching. I am going to use it to better my modeling. Thank you

I've given this 4 out of 5 stars because A) It is free content and B) while I personally didn't learn anything new here I suspect someone at a more beginner level might. The content is a bit outdated; For the type of audience who will likely consume something like this it might be good to point out WSL which has supported Kali Linux for some time now (among other options). What would make this a 5 star course in my opinion is perhaps delving a bit deeper into some of the technical aspects that are a bit glossed over like examples of the networking setup where multiple VMs are involved or maybe a combination of physical devices and VMs. Hybrid set ups are possible, you can connect physical hardware devices to virtual machines to enable interesting testing scenarios. Finally, maybe something on containerization would be ideal as containers are so relevant in today's world.
